This is a fast text search engine, intended for use with source
code. (Pronunciation: roughly as you would pronounce "zooked" in English)

**Note:** This is a [Sourcegraph](https://github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt) fork
of [github.com/google/zoekt](https://github.com/google/zoekt). It is now the
main maintained source of Zoekt.

# INSTRUCTIONS

## Downloading

    go get github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/

## Indexing

### Directory

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-index
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-index .

### Git repository

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-git-index
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-git-index -branches master,stable-1.4 -prefix origin/ .

### Repo repositories

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-{repo-index,mirror-gitiles}
    zoekt-mirror-gitiles -dest ~/repos/ https://gfiber.googlesource.com
    zoekt-repo-index \
        -name gfiber \
        -base_url https://gfiber.googlesource.com/ \
        -manifest_repo ~/repos/gfiber.googlesource.com/manifests.git \
        -repo_cache ~/repos \
        -manifest_rev_prefix=refs/heads/ --rev_prefix= \
        master:default_unrestricted.xml

## Searching

### Web interface

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-webserver
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-webserver -listen :6070

### JSON API

You can retrieve search results as JSON by sending a GET request to zoekt-webserver.

    curl --get \
        --url "http://localhost:6070/search" \
        --data-urlencode "q=ngram f:READ" \
        --data-urlencode "num=50" \
        --data-urlencode "format=json"

The response data is a JSON object. You can refer to [web.ApiSearchResult](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt@6b1df4f8a3d7b34f13ba0cafd8e1a9b3fc728cf0/-/blob/web/api.go?L23:6&subtree=true) to learn about the structure of the object.

### CLI

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt 'ngram f:READ'

## Installation
A more organized installation on a Linux server should use a systemd unit file,
eg.

    [Unit]
    Description=zoekt webserver

    [Service]
    ExecStart=/zoekt/bin/zoekt-webserver -index /zoekt/index -listen :443  --ssl_cert /zoekt/etc/cert.pem   --ssl_key /zoekt/etc/key.pem
    Restart=always

    [Install]
    WantedBy=default.target


# SEARCH SERVICE

Zoekt comes with a small service management program:

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-indexserver

    cat << EOF > config.json
    [{"GithubUser": "username"},
     {"GithubOrg": "org"},
     {"GitilesURL": "https://gerrit.googlesource.com", "Name": "zoekt" }
    ]
    EOF

    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-indexserver -mirror_config config.json

This will mirror all repos under 'github.com/username', 'github.com/org', as
well as the 'zoekt' repository. It will index the repositories.

It takes care of fetching and indexing new data and cleaning up logfiles.

The webserver can be started from a standard service management framework, such
as systemd.


# SYMBOL SEARCH

It is recommended to install [Universal
ctags](https://github.com/universal-ctags/ctags) to improve
ranking. See [here](doc/ctags.md) for more information.


# ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS

Thanks to Han-Wen Nienhuys for creating Zoekt. Thanks to Alexander Neubeck for
coming up with this idea, and helping Han-Wen Nienhuys flesh it out.


# FORK DETAILS

Originally this fork contained some changes that do not make sense to upstream
and or have not yet been upstreamed. However, this is now the defacto source
for Zoekt. This section will remain for historical reasons and contains
outdated information. It can be removed once the dust settles on moving from
google/zoekt to sourcegraph/zoekt. Differences:

- [zoekt-sourcegraph-indexserver](cmd/zoekt-sourcegraph-indexserver/main.go)
  is a Sourcegraph specific command which indexes all enabled repositories on
  Sourcegraph, as well as keeping the indexes up to date.
- We have exposed the API via
  [keegancsmith/rpc](https://github.com/keegancsmith/rpc) (a fork of `net/rpc`
  which supports cancellation).
- Query primitive `BranchesRepos` to efficiently specify a set of repositories to
  search.
- Allow empty shard directories on startup. Needed when starting a fresh
  instance which hasn't indexed anything yet.
- We can return symbol/ctag data in results. Additionally we can run symbol regex queries.
- We search shards in order of repo name and ignore shard ranking.
- Other minor changes.

Assuming you have the gerrit upstream configured, a useful way to see what we
changed is:

``` shellsession
$ git diff gerrit/master -- ':(exclude)vendor/' ':(exclude)Gopkg*'
```

This regular expression will fail to do what it probably intends to do. Let's break it down:

* `/n/a|e|i|o|u//n`
   * `/n/`: This part tries to match the literal characters "n/".
   * `a|e|i|o|u`: This part correctly matches any single vowel.
   * `//n`: This part has two problems:
      * It introduces a syntax error because the regex ends with an unterminated regular expression literal.
      * The `n` flag at the end is likely intended to be a global flag (`g`), but it's misplaced.

**What the regex probably intends to do (and how to fix it):**

The regex likely aims to find all vowels in a text. Here's the corrected version:

```regexp
/[aeiou]/g
```

**Explanation:**

* `[aeiou]`: This character class matches any single character within the brackets (i.e., any vowel).
* `g`: This global flag ensures that the regex doesn't stop after the first match but continues to find all occurrences of vowels in the input string.

**Example Usage:**

```javascript
const text = "This is a test string.";
const vowelRegex = /[aeiou]/g;
const matches = text.match(vowelRegex); 

console.log(matches); // Output: ["i", "i", "a", "e", "i"]
```

Your code implements a fast text search engine called Zoekt, specifically designed for searching source code. Here's a breakdown:

    - `SearchOptions`: Controls search behavior, such as maximum match counts, context lines, and scoring method.

    - `SearchResult`: Contains the search results, including matching files, repositories, and statistics.

    - This codebase is a fork of Google's Zoekt, with additional features and modifications for Sourcegraph.

The `DirectoryWatcher` in `mocked/codebase_context/shards/watcher.go` monitors a directory for changes to Zoekt index shard files and updates the search index accordingly. Here's a breakdown:

1. **Initialization:**
   - It takes the directory path and a `shardLoader` as input.
   - It stores timestamps of existing shard files in the directory.

2. **Scanning:**
   - It scans the directory for shard files (`*.zoekt`).
   - It identifies the latest versions of shards based on filenames.
   - It compares timestamps of shard files with its stored timestamps.
   - It determines which shards need to be loaded or dropped based on timestamp changes.
   - It calls the `shardLoader` to load new shards and drop outdated ones.

3. **Watching:**
   - It uses `fsnotify` to watch the directory for file system events.
   - When a change is detected, it triggers a scan to update the index.

4. **Handling Changes:**
   - It loads new or updated shard files into the index.
   - It unloads deleted or outdated shard files from the index.

**In essence, the `DirectoryWatcher` ensures that the search index remains consistent with the contents of the shard directory by loading new shards and unloading outdated ones as changes occur.**

Goroutines are lightweight, independently executing functions or methods within a Go program. They are managed by the Go runtime and provide a way to achieve concurrency in your code.

Here's a breakdown of how goroutines work:

**1. Creation:**

You create a goroutine by placing the keyword `go` before a function or method call. This tells the Go runtime to execute the function concurrently.

```go
go myFunction() // Creates a goroutine that executes myFunction concurrently
```

**2. Lightweight Execution:**

*   Goroutines are lightweight compared to operating system threads. They have a smaller memory footprint (typically starting at 2KB) and lower context-switching overhead.
*   The Go runtime manages a pool of OS threads and multiplexes goroutines onto these threads. This means you can have thousands or even millions of goroutines running concurrently on a system with a limited number of OS threads.

**3. Concurrency, Not Parallelism:**

*   Goroutines enable concurrency, which means multiple tasks can be in progress at the same time. However, it doesn't guarantee parallelism (simultaneous execution on multiple cores).
*   The Go runtime scheduler determines when and how goroutines are executed on the available OS threads. By default, Go programs run on all available CPU cores, allowing for potential parallelism if the code is structured to take advantage of it.

**4. Communication and Synchronization:**

*   Goroutines communicate with each other primarily through channels, which are typed message queues. Channels provide a safe and synchronized way to share data between concurrently executing goroutines.
*   Synchronization mechanisms like mutexes and wait groups are also available for more complex coordination scenarios.

**Example:**

```go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "time"
)

func printNumbers() {
    for i := 1; i <= 5; i++ {
        fmt.Println("Number:", i)
        time.Sleep(time.Millisecond * 500)
    }
}

func main() {
    go printNumbers() // Start printNumbers in a goroutine

    fmt.Println("Main function started")

    time.Sleep(time.Second * 3) // Give the goroutine time to run

    fmt.Println("Main function exiting")
}
```

In this example:

1.  `printNumbers` is executed in a separate goroutine.
2.  The `main` function continues to execute concurrently.
3.  The `time.Sleep` calls simulate work being done.

**Key Points:**

*   Goroutines are a powerful tool for concurrent programming in Go.
*   They are lightweight and efficient, allowing you to create highly concurrent programs.
*   Channels are the preferred way to communicate and synchronize data between goroutines.
*   Understanding the distinction between concurrency and parallelism is crucial when working with goroutines.

This is a fast text search engine, intended for use with source
code. (Pronunciation: roughly as you would pronounce "zooked" in English)

**Note:** This is a [Sourcegraph](https://github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt) fork
of [github.com/google/zoekt](https://github.com/google/zoekt). It is now the
main maintained source of Zoekt.

# INSTRUCTIONS

## Downloading

    go get github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/

## Indexing

### Directory

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-index
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-index .

### Git repository

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-git-index
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-git-index -branches master,stable-1.4 -prefix origin/ .

### Repo repositories

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-{repo-index,mirror-gitiles}
    zoekt-mirror-gitiles -dest ~/repos/ https://gfiber.googlesource.com
    zoekt-repo-index /n        -name gfiber /n        -base_url https://gfiber.googlesource.com/ /n        -manifest_repo ~/repos/gfiber.googlesource.com/manifests.git /n        -repo_cache ~/repos /n        -manifest_rev_prefix=refs/heads/ --rev_prefix= /n        master:default_unrestricted.xml

## Searching

### Web interface

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-webserver
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-webserver -listen :6070

### JSON API

You can retrieve search results as JSON by sending a GET request to zoekt-webserver.

    curl --get /n        --url "http://localhost:6070/search" /n        --data-urlencode "q=ngram f:READ" /n        --data-urlencode "num=50" /n        --data-urlencode "format=json"

The response data is a JSON object. You can refer to [web.ApiSearchResult](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt@6b1df4f8a3d7b34f13ba0cafd8e1a9b3fc728cf0/-/blob/web/api.go?L23:6&subtree=true) to learn about the structure of the object.

### CLI

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt 'ngram f:READ'

## Installation
A more organized installation on a Linux server should use a systemd unit file,
eg.

    [Unit]
    Description=zoekt webserver

    [Service]
    ExecStart=/zoekt/bin/zoekt-webserver -index /zoekt/index -listen :443  --ssl_cert /zoekt/etc/cert.pem   --ssl_key /zoekt/etc/key.pem
    Restart=always

    [Install]
    WantedBy=default.target


# SEARCH SERVICE

Zoekt comes with a small service management program:

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-indexserver

    cat << EOF > config.json
    [{"GithubUser": "username"},
     {"GithubOrg": "org"},
     {"GitilesURL": "https://gerrit.googlesource.com", "Name": "zoekt" }
    ]
    EOF

    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-indexserver -mirror_config config.json

This will mirror all repos under 'github.com/username', 'github.com/org', as
well as the 'zoekt' repository. It will index the repositories.

It takes care of fetching and indexing new data and cleaning up logfiles.

The webserver can be started from a standard service management framework, such
as systemd.


# SYMBOL SEARCH

It is recommended to install [Universal
ctags](https://github.com/universal-ctags/ctags) to improve
ranking. See [here](doc/ctags.md) for more information.

In Go, slices are a key data structure that provide a more powerful and flexible way to work with sequences of elements compared to arrays. Heres a detailed explanation of how slices work:

### Basics of Slices

1. **Definition**:
   - A slice is a descriptor for a contiguous segment of an underlying array and provides much more flexibility than an array.
   - Unlike arrays, slices are dynamically-sized.

2. **Declaration**:
   - Slices can be declared just like arrays but without specifying the size.
   - Example:
     ```go
     var s []int // declares a slice of integers
     ```

3. **Initialization**:
   - Slices can be initialized using a slice literal, which is similar to an array literal but without the size.
   - Example:
     ```go
     s := []int{1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
     ```

4. **Creating Slices**:
   - Slices can be created using the built-in `make` function.
   - Example:
     ```go
     s := make([]int, 5) // creates a slice of integers with length 5
     ```

5. **Slicing an Array or Slice**:
   - You can create a slice from an array or another slice.
   - Example:
     ```go
     arr := [5]int{1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
     s := arr[1:4] // creates a slice [2 3 4] from the array
     ```

### Slice Internals

A slice is a descriptor of an array segment and consists of three components:
1. **Pointer**: Points to the first element of the array that is accessible through the slice.
2. **Length**: The number of elements in the slice.
3. **Capacity**: The number of elements in the underlying array starting from the element the slice points to.

### Operations on Slices

1. **Appending**:
   - You can append elements to a slice using the built-in `append` function.
   - Example:
     ```go
     s := []int{1, 2, 3}
     s = append(s, 4, 5) // s is now [1 2 3 4 5]
     ```

2. **Copying**:
   - You can copy elements from one slice to another using the `copy` function.
   - Example:
     ```go
     src := []int{1, 2, 3}
     dst := make([]int, len(src))
     copy(dst, src) // dst is now [1 2 3]
     ```

3. **Length and Capacity**:
   - You can get the length and capacity of a slice using the `len` and `cap` functions.
   - Example:
     ```go
     s := []int{1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
     fmt.Println(len(s)) // prints 5
     fmt.Println(cap(s)) // prints 5
     ```

### Example Usage

Here is a simple example demonstrating the use of slices in Go:

```go:example/slices.go
package main

import "fmt"

func main() {
    // Declare and initialize a slice
    s := []int{1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
    fmt.Println("Initial slice:", s)

    // Append elements to the slice
    s = append(s, 6, 7)
    fmt.Println("After appending:", s)

    // Create a slice from another slice
    subSlice := s[2:5]
    fmt.Println("Sub-slice:", subSlice)

    // Copy a slice
    copiedSlice := make([]int, len(s))
    copy(copiedSlice, s)
    fmt.Println("Copied slice:", copiedSlice)

    // Length and capacity
    fmt.Println("Length:", len(s))
    fmt.Println("Capacity:", cap(s))
}
```

### Conclusion

Slices in Go provide a powerful way to work with sequences of elements, offering flexibility and efficiency. They are built on top of arrays and provide dynamic resizing, making them a fundamental part of Go programming.

Upgrading your Python version can be done in several ways depending on your operating system. Here are the general steps for the most common operating systems:

### On Ubuntu/Debian:

1. **Update the package list:**
   ```sh
   sudo apt update
   ```

2. **Install the new version of Python:**
   ```sh
   sudo apt install python3.x
   ```
   Replace `3.x` with the version you want to install, e.g., `python3.9`.

3. **Update the `python3` symlink:**
   ```sh
   sudo update-alternatives --install /usr/bin/python3 python3 /usr/bin/python3.x 1
   sudo update-alternatives --config python3
   ```
   Follow the prompts to select the new version.

### On macOS:

1. **Install Homebrew** (if you haven't already):
   ```sh
   /bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/HEAD/install.sh)"
   ```

2. **Install the new version of Python:**
   ```sh
   brew install python@3.x
   ```
   Replace `3.x` with the version you want to install, e.g., `python@3.9`.

3. **Update the `python3` symlink:**
   ```sh
   brew link --overwrite python@3.x
   ```

### On Windows:

1. **Download the installer** for the new version of Python from the [official Python website](https://www.python.org/downloads/).

2. **Run the installer** and follow the prompts. Make sure to check the box that says "Add Python to PATH".

3. **Verify the installation:**
   Open a new Command Prompt and run:
   ```sh
   python --version
   ```

### Using `pyenv` (Cross-platform):

`pyenv` is a popular tool for managing multiple Python versions.

1. **Install `pyenv`:**
   Follow the installation instructions from the [pyenv GitHub repository](https://github.com/pyenv/pyenv#installation).

2. **Install the new version of Python:**
   ```sh
   pyenv install 3.x.x
   ```
   Replace `3.x.x` with the version you want to install, e.g., `3.9.1`.

3. **Set the global Python version:**
   ```sh
   pyenv global 3.x.x
   ```

4. **Verify the installation:**
   ```sh
   python --version
   ```

These steps should help you upgrade your Python version on various operating systems. If you encounter any issues, please provide more details about your environment and the specific problem you're facing.

    [{"GithubUser": "username"},

- We search shards in order of repo name and ignore shard ranking.
- Other minor changes.

Assuming you have the gerrit upstream configured, a useful way to see what we
changed is:

``` shellsession
$ git diff gerrit/master -- ':(exclude)vendor/' ':(exclude)Gopkg*'
```

Goroutines are a fundamental feature in Go that enable concurrent execution of functions. They are lightweight threads managed by the Go runtime. Here's a brief overview of how they work and how you can use them:

### How Goroutines Work

1. **Concurrency**: Goroutines allow you to run functions concurrently. They are more lightweight than traditional threads, which means you can run thousands of goroutines without significant overhead.
2. **Scheduling**: The Go runtime includes a scheduler that manages goroutines. It multiplexes goroutines onto a smaller number of OS threads, which helps in efficient execution.
3. **Communication**: Goroutines often communicate using channels, which are typed conduits through which you can send and receive values.

### Basic Usage

Here's a simple example to demonstrate how to create and use goroutines in Go:

```go:main.go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "time"
)

func printNumbers() {
    for i := 1; i <= 5; i++ {
        fmt.Println(i)
        time.Sleep(1 * time.Second)
    }
}

func main() {
    go printNumbers() // Start printNumbers in a new goroutine

    // Keep the main function alive for a while to see the output of the goroutine
    time.Sleep(6 * time.Second)
    fmt.Println("Main function finished")
}
```

### Explanation

1. **Function Definition**: The `printNumbers` function prints numbers from 1 to 5 with a 1-second delay between each print.
2. **Starting a Goroutine**: In the `main` function, `go printNumbers()` starts the `printNumbers` function in a new goroutine.
3. **Main Function Sleep**: The `main` function sleeps for 6 seconds to allow the goroutine to complete its execution. Without this, the program would terminate before the goroutine finishes.

### Synchronization

To properly synchronize goroutines, you can use channels or synchronization primitives like `sync.WaitGroup`. Here's an example using a channel:

```go:main.go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "time"
)

func printNumbers(done chan bool) {
    for i := 1; i <= 5; i++ {
        fmt.Println(i)
        time.Sleep(1 * time.Second)
    }
    done <- true // Signal that the goroutine is done
}

func main() {
    done := make(chan bool)
    go printNumbers(done)

    <-done // Wait for the goroutine to finish
    fmt.Println("Main function finished")
}
```

### Explanation

1. **Channel Creation**: A channel `done` is created to signal when the goroutine is done.
2. **Channel Communication**: The `printNumbers` function sends a `true` value to the `done` channel after it finishes execution.
3. **Waiting for Completion**: The `main` function waits to receive a value from the `done` channel, ensuring that the goroutine completes before the program terminates.

Goroutines are a powerful feature in Go, enabling efficient and scalable concurrent programming.

Here's a breakdown of how slices work in Go, along with some key points to keep in mind:

**Understanding Slices**

* **Dynamic Arrays:** Slices are like dynamic arrays in other languages. They provide a way to store a sequence of elements of the same type, but unlike arrays, their size can grow or shrink as needed.
* **Underlying Array:**  A slice is a reference to an underlying array. It doesn't directly own the data; it simply points to a portion of an array.
* **Length and Capacity:**
    * **Length:** The number of elements currently in the slice.
    * **Capacity:** The maximum number of elements the slice can hold without reallocation. The capacity is always greater than or equal to the length.

**Key Operations**

1. **Creating Slices:**

   * **Literal:** `var mySlice []int = []int{1, 2, 3}`
   * **Make:** `mySlice := make([]int, 5)` (Creates a slice with length 5 and capacity 5)
   * **From an Array:** `mySlice := myArray[1:3]` (Creates a slice referencing elements 1 and 2 of the array)

2. **Accessing Elements:**

   * `mySlice[index]` (Accesses the element at the specified index)

3. **Appending Elements:**

   * `mySlice = append(mySlice, newElement)` (Appends a new element to the end of the slice)
   * If the slice's capacity is reached, Go will automatically reallocate a larger underlying array, copying the existing elements and then appending the new element.

4. **Slicing:**

   * `mySlice[start:end]` (Creates a new slice referencing elements from `start` (inclusive) to `end` (exclusive))
   * `mySlice[start:]` (Creates a new slice referencing elements from `start` to the end of the original slice)
   * `mySlice[:end]` (Creates a new slice referencing elements from the beginning to `end` (exclusive))

5. **Iterating:**

   * **For Loop:**
     ```go
     for i := 0; i < len(mySlice); i++ {
         fmt.Println(mySlice[i])
     }
     ```
   * **Range:**
     ```go
     for index, value := range mySlice {
         fmt.Println(index, value)
     }
     ```

**Example**

```go
package main

import "fmt"

func main() {
    // Create a slice with length 3 and capacity 3
    mySlice := make([]int, 3)

    // Assign values to the slice
    mySlice[0] = 10
    mySlice[1] = 20
    mySlice[2] = 30

    // Print the slice
    fmt.Println("Original slice:", mySlice)

    // Append a new element
    mySlice = append(mySlice, 40)

    // Print the updated slice
    fmt.Println("Updated slice:", mySlice)

    // Create a new slice referencing elements 1 and 2
    newSlice := mySlice[1:3]

    // Print the new slice
    fmt.Println("New slice:", newSlice)
}
```

**Important Notes**

* **Pass by Reference:** When you pass a slice to a function, you're passing a reference to the underlying array. Changes made to the slice within the function will affect the original slice.
* **Zero Value:** The zero value of a slice is `nil`. A nil slice has a length and capacity of 0.
* **Memory Management:** Go handles memory management for slices. When a slice is no longer needed, the underlying array's memory is automatically reclaimed.

Let me know if you'd like to explore specific slice operations or have any more questions!

Goroutines are lightweight threads managed by the Go runtime. Here's a breakdown of how they work:

**1. Concurrency, Not Parallelism:**

* **Concurrency:** Goroutines enable you to run multiple tasks seemingly simultaneously. This means tasks can be interleaved, giving the illusion of parallelism.
* **Parallelism:** True parallelism requires multiple CPU cores. While Go can utilize multiple cores, goroutines themselves don't guarantee parallelism. The Go runtime decides how to schedule goroutines onto available cores.

**2. The Go Runtime's Role:**

* **Scheduling:** The Go runtime manages a pool of goroutines and schedules them onto available threads. It uses a work-stealing scheduler, where idle threads "steal" tasks from busy threads.
* **Communication:** Goroutines communicate using channels, which are typed message queues. This allows goroutines to exchange data and synchronize their operations.

**3. Creating Goroutines:**

* **`go` Keyword:** You create a goroutine by using the `go` keyword before a function call.
* **Example:**
   ```go:main.go
   package main

   import "fmt"

   func main() {
       go sayHello("World")
       fmt.Println("Main goroutine continues...")
   }

   func sayHello(name string) {
       fmt.Println("Hello,", name)
   }
   ```

**4. Channels for Communication:**

* **Channels:** Channels are typed communication channels that allow goroutines to send and receive data.
* **Example:**
   ```go:main.go
   package main

   import (
       "fmt"
       "time"
   )

   func main() {
       c := make(chan string)
       go func() {
           time.Sleep(2 * time.Second)
           c <- "Hello from goroutine!"
       }()
       message := <-c
       fmt.Println(message)
   }
   ```

**5. Advantages of Goroutines:**

* **Lightweight:** Goroutines are much lighter than operating system threads, requiring less memory and resources.
* **Concurrency:** They provide a simple and efficient way to achieve concurrency.
* **Built-in Support:** Go's runtime provides built-in support for goroutines and channels, making them easy to use.

**6. Key Concepts:**

* **`go` keyword:** Creates a new goroutine.
* **`chan` keyword:** Creates a new channel.
* **`<-` operator:** Sends and receives data on channels.
* **`select` statement:** Allows goroutines to wait on multiple channels.

**7. Example: Concurrent Web Server:**

```go:main.go
package main

import (
	"fmt"
	"net/http"
)

func handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
	fmt.Fprintf(w, "Hello, world!\n")
}

func main() {
	http.HandleFunc("/", handler)
	fmt.Println("Server started on port 8080")
	go http.ListenAndServe(":8080", nil)
	// Main goroutine continues to do other tasks
	// ...
}
```

**In summary:** Goroutines are a powerful feature of Go that make it easy to write concurrent programs. They are lightweight, efficient, and well-integrated with the Go runtime. By understanding how goroutines work, you can leverage their benefits to build robust and scalable applications.

The `limit.go` file in the `zoekt` package implements functionality to limit the number of displayed search results, both in terms of the number of files and the number of matches within each file.

Here's a breakdown of its key functions:

* **`SortAndTruncateFiles`:** This function takes a list of `FileMatch` objects (representing files matching the search query) and sorts them. It then applies a `DisplayTruncator` function to truncate the list based on the search options. This ensures that only a limited number of files and matches are displayed to the user.

* **`DisplayTruncator`:** This is a function type that represents a stateful function for truncating search results. It takes a list of `FileMatch` objects as input and returns a truncated list along with a boolean flag indicating whether there are more results to be displayed.

* **`NewDisplayTruncator`:** This function creates a new `DisplayTruncator` based on the search options. It checks for limits on the number of files and matches to be displayed and returns a `DisplayTruncator` that enforces these limits.

* **`limitMatches`:** This function is responsible for limiting the number of matches within each `FileMatch` object. It takes a list of `FileMatch` objects, a limit, and a boolean flag indicating whether to chunk matches (group matches within a file into chunks). # INSTRUCTIONS

## Downloading

    go get github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/

## Indexing

### Directory

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-index
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-index .

### Git repository

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-git-index

        -repo_cache ~/repos \
        -manifest_rev_prefix=refs/heads/ --rev_prefix= \
        master:default_unrestricted.xml

## Searching

### Web interface

    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-webserver -listen :6070

### JSON API

You can retrieve search results as JSON by sending a GET request to zoekt-webserver.

### CLI

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt 'ngram f:READ'

## Installation
A more organized installation on a Linux server should use a systemd unit file,
eg.

    [Unit]
    Description=zoekt webserver

    [Service]
    ExecStart=/zoekt/bin/zoekt-webserver -index /zoekt/index -listen :443  --ssl_cert /zoekt/etc/cert.pem   --ssl_key /zoekt/etc/key.pem
    Restart=always

    [Install]
    WantedBy=default.target

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-indexserver

In Go, slices are a fundamental data type that provide a flexible and efficient way to work with sequences of elements. They are built on top of arrays and provide a way to access and manipulate a subset of an array's elements.

Here's how slices work in Go:

1. **Creating a Slice**:
   - You can create a slice using the built-in `make` function: `slice := make([]type, length, capacity)`. The `length` parameter specifies the initial length of the slice, and the `capacity` parameter specifies the underlying array's capacity.
   - You can also create a slice by slicing an array: `array := [5]int{1, 2, 3, 4, 5}` and `slice := array[1:4]` (creates a slice with elements at indices 1, 2, and 3).

2. **Accessing Elements**:
   - You can access individual elements of a slice using the index notation: `slice[index]`.
   - Slices are zero-indexed, meaning the first element is at index 0.

3. **Modifying Elements**:
   - You can modify elements of a slice by assigning new values to the corresponding indices: `slice[2] = 42`.

4. **Length and Capacity**:
   - The length of a slice is the number of elements it contains, and you can get it using the built-in `len` function: `length := len(slice)`.
   - The capacity of a slice is the number of elements in the underlying array, starting from the first element in the slice. You can get it using the built-in `cap` function: `capacity := cap(slice)`.
   - When you create a slice from an array or another slice, the capacity is set to the maximum elements available in the underlying array, counting from the start of the new slice.

5. **Appending Elements**:
   - You can append elements to a slice using the built-in `append` function: `slice = append(slice, 42, 43)`.
   - If the underlying array doesn't have enough capacity to accommodate the new elements, a new array is allocated with a larger capacity, and the existing elements are copied over.

6. **Slicing**:
   - You can create a new slice by slicing an existing slice: `newSlice := slice[2:4]` (creates a new slice with elements at indices 2 and 3 from the original slice).
   - Slicing doesn't copy the underlying array; it creates a new slice that shares the same underlying array as the original slice.

7. **Nil Slices**:
   - A nil slice has a length and capacity of 0 and has no underlying array.
   - You can check if a slice is nil using the comparison operator: `if slice == nil { ... }`.

8. **Useful Functions**:
   - The `slices` package in the Go standard library provides utility functions for working with slices, such as `slices.Contains`, `slices.Sort`, `slices.Index`, and more.

Slices in Go are powerful and efficient because they provide a way to work with arrays without the need for explicit memory management or resizing. They automatically grow as needed and allow for easy manipulation of sequences of elements.

   - **pyenv** (Linux/macOS/Windows): Install pyenv, then use `pyenv install 3.x.y` to install a specific Python version and `pyenv global 3.x.y` to set it as the global version.
   - **conda** (cross-platform): Install Anaconda or Miniconda, create a new environment with the desired Python version using `conda create -n myenv python=3.x`, and activate it with `conda activate myenv`.

   - On Ubuntu/Debian: `sudo add-apt-repository ppa:deadsnakes/ppa` then `sudo apt install python3.x`

This is a fast text search engine, intended for use with source
code. (Pronunciation: roughly as you would pronounce "zooked" in English)

**Note:** This is a [Sourcegraph](https://github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt) fork
of [github.com/google/zoekt](https://github.com/google/zoekt). It is now the
main maintained source of Zoekt.

# INSTRUCTIONS

## Downloading

    go get github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/

## Indexing

### Directory

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-index
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-index .

### Git repository

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-git-index
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-git-index -branches master,stable-1.4 -prefix origin/ .

### Repo repositories

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-{repo-index,mirror-gitiles}
    zoekt-mirror-gitiles -dest ~/repos/ https://gfiber.googlesource.com
    zoekt-repo-index \
        -name gfiber \
        -base_url https://gfiber.googlesource.com/ \
        -manifest_repo ~/repos/gfiber.googlesource.com/manifests.git \
        -repo_cache ~/repos \
        -manifest_rev_prefix=refs/heads/ --rev_prefix= \
        master:default_unrestricted.xml

## Searching

### Web interface

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-webserver
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-webserver -listen :6070

### JSON API

You can retrieve search results as JSON by sending a GET request to zoekt-webserver.

    curl --get \
        --url "http://localhost:6070/search" \
        --data-urlencode "q=ngram f:READ" \
        --data-urlencode "num=50" \
        --data-urlencode "format=json"

The response data is a JSON object. You can refer to [web.ApiSearchResult](https://sourcegraph.com/github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt@6b1df4f8a3d7b34f13ba0cafd8e1a9b3fc728cf0/-/blob/web/api.go?L23:6&subtree=true) to learn about the structure of the object.

### CLI

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt
    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt 'ngram f:READ'

## Installation
A more organized installation on a Linux server should use a systemd unit file,
eg.

    [Unit]
    Description=zoekt webserver

    [Service]
    ExecStart=/zoekt/bin/zoekt-webserver -index /zoekt/index -listen :443  --ssl_cert /zoekt/etc/cert.pem   --ssl_key /zoekt/etc/key.pem
    Restart=always

    [Install]
    WantedBy=default.target


# SEARCH SERVICE

Zoekt comes with a small service management program:

    go install github.com/sourcegraph/zoekt/cmd/zoekt-indexserver

    cat << EOF > config.json
    [{"GithubUser": "username"},
     {"GithubOrg": "org"},
     {"GitilesURL": "https://gerrit.googlesource.com", "Name": "zoekt" }
    ]
    EOF

    $GOPATH/bin/zoekt-indexserver -mirror_config config.json

This will mirror all repos under 'github.com/username', 'github.com/org', as
well as the 'zoekt' repository. It will index the repositories.

It takes care of fetching and indexing new data and cleaning up logfiles.

The webserver can be started from a standard service management framework, such
as systemd.


# SYMBOL SEARCH

It is recommended to install [Universal
ctags](https://github.com/universal-ctags/ctags) to improve
ranking. See [here](doc/ctags.md) for more information.


# ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS

Thanks to Han-Wen Nienhuys for creating Zoekt. Thanks to Alexander Neubeck for
coming up with this idea, and helping Han-Wen Nienhuys flesh it out.


# FORK DETAILS

Originally this fork contained some changes that do not make sense to upstream
and or have not yet been upstreamed. However, this is now the defacto source
for Zoekt. This section will remain for historical reasons and contains
outdated information. It can be removed once the dust settles on moving from
google/zoekt to sourcegraph/zoekt. Differences:

- [zoekt-sourcegraph-indexserver](cmd/zoekt-sourcegraph-indexserver/main.go)
  is a Sourcegraph specific command which indexes all enabled repositories on
  Sourcegraph, as well as keeping the indexes up to date.
- We have exposed the API via
  [keegancsmith/rpc](https://github.com/keegancsmith/rpc) (a fork of `net/rpc`
  which supports cancellation).
- Query primitive `BranchesRepos` to efficiently specify a set of repositories to
  search.
- Allow empty shard directories on startup. Needed when starting a fresh
  instance which hasn't indexed anything yet.
- We can return symbol/ctag data in results. Additionally we can run symbol regex queries.
- We search shards in order of repo name and ignore shard ranking.
- Other minor changes.

Assuming you have the gerrit upstream configured, a useful way to see what we
changed is:

``` shellsession
$ git diff gerrit/master -- ':(exclude)vendor/' ':(exclude)Gopkg*'
```

The `limit.go` file in the provided codebase context contains functions related to limiting and truncating the search results based on the specified options. Here's a summary of what the file does:

1. `SortAndTruncateFiles` is a convenience function that sorts the `FileMatch` slice and then truncates it based on the `SearchOptions`.

2. `DisplayTruncator` is a type alias for a function that takes a slice of `FileMatch` and returns a truncated slice along with a boolean indicating if there are more results to be displayed.

3. `NewDisplayTruncator` creates a `DisplayTruncator` function based on the `SearchOptions`. It enforces limits on the maximum number of documents (`MaxDocDisplayCount`) and matches (`MaxMatchDisplayCount`) to be displayed.

4. `limitMatches` is a helper function that limits the number of matches in each `FileMatch` based on the `chunkMatches` option. It calls either `limitChunkMatches` or `limitLineMatches` depending on the value of `chunkMatches`.

5. `limitChunkMatches` limits the number of `ChunkMatches` in a `FileMatch`. It truncates the `Ranges`, `SymbolInfo`, and `Content` fields of each `ChunkMatch` based on the specified limit.

6. `limitLineMatches` limits the number of `LineMatches` in a `FileMatch` by truncating the `LineFragments` field of each `LineMatch`.

In summary, the `limit.go` file provides functionality to limit and truncate search results based on various options, such as the maximum number of documents, matches, and line fragments to display. This can be useful for optimizing the display of search results and preventing excessive data from being returned.
